  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 15-21.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The people's sin offering, burnt off, ring, meat offering, and peace offerings follow. The meat offering is said to have been ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "burnt upon the altar, beside the burnt sacrifice of the morning",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is probable that, on this occasion, the people's burnt offering, which consisted of a calf and a lamb, took the place of the ordinary morning sacrifice of a lamb (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 29:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Aaron is said to have ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "offered the burnt offering according to the manner",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or, as it is given in the margin, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ordinance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, he burnt the flesh on the altar (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 1:7-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); he also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "burnt",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "handful",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the meat offering, and he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "burnt the fat",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the peace offering, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "upon the altar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He had previously burnt the fat of his own sin offering, and the flesh of his burnt offering. Fire, therefore, was present upon the altar, and was used by Aaron, as by Moses, for sacrificial purposes ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "before",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the fire came out from the Lord as described in verse 24. Leviticus 9:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of the sacrifices of the nation, Aaron presented the sin-offering in the same manner as the first, i.e., the one offered for himself (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 9:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). The blood of this sin-offering, which was presented for the congregation, was not brought into the holy place according to the rule laid down in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., but only applied to the horns of the altar of burnt-offering; for the same reason as in the previous case (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 9:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".), viz., because the object was not to expiate any particular sin, or the sins of the congregation that had been committed in the course of time and remained unatoned for, but simply to place the sacrificial service of the congregation in its proper relation to the Lord. Aaron was reproved by Moses, however, for having burned the flesh (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 10:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".), but was able to justify it (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 10:16-20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The sin-offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") was also offered \"according to the right\" (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Then followed the meat-offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 9:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), of which Aaron burned a handful upon the altar (according to the rule in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 2:1-2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He offered this in addition to the morning burnt-offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 29:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), to which a meat-offering also belonged (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 29:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and with which, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., the special meat-offering of the priests was associated. Last of all (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 9:18-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") there followed the peace-offering, which was also carried out according to the general rule. In המכסּה, \"the covering\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 9:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the two fat portions mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are included. The fat portions were laid upon the breast-pieces by the sons of Aaron, and then handed by them to Aaron, the fat to be burned upon the altar, the breast to be waved along with the right leg, according to the instructions in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:30-36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The meat-offering of pastry, which belonged to the peace-offering according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:12-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is not specially mentioned. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]